We begin with a scenario with high levels of faulty values, which is where one would expect accounting for errors in the MVs to matter the most. Figure 1 displays key results for the coefficient for math in the regression for Y1subscriptğ‘Œ1Y_{1} in the high seed, high fault (HSHF) scenario. We focus on this coefficient because it is the most important predictor of Y1subscriptğ‘Œ1Y_{1} by far, as evident in the final row of Table 2.
The posterior means based on BLASE with the
appropriately concentrated or diffuse priors tend to be similar to those based on the analysis with the PB data. Not surprisingly, using the poorly concentrated prior distribution worsens the performance of BLASE. Figure 1a, as well as Table 2, also suggest that accounting for potential errors in the MVs can improve inferences relative to treating the faulty MV as an error-free BV. This is corroborated in Figure 1b, which shows that allowing the file matching algorithm to change faulty MVs from their reported values can increase match rates.

We next examine the performance of BLASE with low levels of faulty values, focusing on the high seed, low fault (HSLF) scenario. Key results are displayed in Figure 2 and Table 2.
Here, BLASE with the CA or D priors continues to estimate the coefficient of math reasonably well.
However, gains from accounting for the faulty MVs are not as large as in the HSLF scenario. Specifically, the RMSE and match rates for BLASE with the CA or D priors are similar to those for the model that treats the faulty MV as an error-free BV.

Focusing on results in Table 2 for the diffuse prior distribution, we can discern general patterns over the four simulation scenarios. First, in both HF scenarios, the results suggest that applying BLASE tends to result in improvements in PMR, lower average RMSE, and more accurate estimates of the Y1subscriptğ‘Œ1Y_{1} model coefficients than a model which incorrectly assumes that faulty MVs can be used as BVs. In contrast, in low fault scenarios there is less to be gained by applying BLASE. Second, in the HSLF scenario, BLASE using the CA or D priors can offer improvements, albeit smaller than those for the HSHF scenario. Apparently, even when only a modest number of records are reported with errors, BLASE can leverage the information in the T1subscriptğ‘‡1T_{1} seeds to identify plausible moves. Third, in the LSLF scenario, BLASE is not as effective as treating all the variables as BVs. Without adequate numbers of T1subscriptğ‘‡1T_{1} seeds, BLASE does not have enough information to determine accurate moves.
We note that, although not apparent from Table 2, in scenarios with low numbers of T1subscriptğ‘‡1T_{1} seeds, none of the file matching algorithms provide accurate estimates of the coefficients; see the supplementary material for supporting results.

references: In this section we present further simulation results from the BLASE simulation discussed in Section 5 of the main paper. These results are summarized in Table 6 in this supplement, which is the same as Table 2 in the main paper. For each of the four simulation groups, we provide figures for (1) PMR, (2) RMSE and (3) parameter estimation for the Y1subscriptğ‘Œ1Y_{1} regression. Supplementary Table 7 summarizes the parameter estimation from the Y2subscriptğ‘Œ2Y_{2} regression, but because the behavior mimics that observed in the Y1subscriptğ‘Œ1Y_{1} regression estimates, we do not include plots for the Y2subscriptğ‘Œ2Y_{2} estimates.

We begin with a scenario with high levels of faulty values, which is where one would expect accounting for errors in the MVs to matter the most. Recall that the focus of these simulation studies is to examine potential gains when error in the MVs is addressed in the model. Consider Figure 5. The posterior means based on BLASE with the appropriately concentrated or diffuse priors tend to be similar to those based on the analysis with the PB data. Not surprisingly, using the poorly concentrated prior distribution worsens the performance of BLASE. Figure 5, as well as Table 6, also suggest that accounting for potential errors in the MVs can improve inferences relative to treating the faulty MV as an error-free BV. This is corroborated in Figure 6a, which shows that allowing the file matching algorithm to change faulty MVs from their reported values can increase match rates. While some increase in PMR in BLASE is expected due to chance, Figure 6a shows a sizable increase in PMR at all three prior settings. The increase in PMR for BLASE in the HSHF scenario is accompanied by a reduction in RMSE (Figure 6b) and more accurate estimates of three of the four linking parameters (Figure 5).
